  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "The first law of motion (Newton's First Law) states that an object in motion will stay in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an external force. An object at rest will stay at rest unless acted upon by an external force.\n\nSo, when you stop a rolling pin that's rolling, you are applying an **external force** to it. The type of force you are applying is typically a **contact force**, specifically a **frictional force** and/or a **muscular force**.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Muscular Force:** The force generated by your muscles as you physically reach out and grab the rolling pin.\n*   **Frictional Force:** Once your hand makes contact with the rolling pin, the friction between your hand and the surface of the rolling pin helps to slow it down.\n\n**In summary, the force you apply to stop a rolling pin is a combination of muscular force and frictional force.**\n",
